Have you recruited talent for the company?
That way you don't let your competitors steal it.
The economy is still a labor market dominated largely by workers, and the same is true of the most desirable workers -- talent.
Here are some suggestions to help you maintain it in the workplace
I'm not going anywhere.
Despite the rise recorded last month, Israel's unemployment rate remains among the lowest in the world, and in the top ten among OECD countries, with a rate of 3.5% (150.6 thousand unemployed, according to the ILO).
That is, the economy is still in a labor market dominated mostly by workers, and the same is true of the most sought-after workers -- talent.
As for those professionals and managers who are proven centers of knowledge, experience and ability, trends in the labor market teach that competition for talent, as it is defined by employers, is still at its peak.
What this means for employers is that in the current job market situation, they don't have the luxury of resting on their laurels even a minute after recruiting a desired talent, because as soon as he enters the company, another company will already be trying to kidnap him.
That is, the competition for talent is so fierce that even after recruitment, many will continue to receive a plethora of tempting job offers, with 30 percent of employees actually leaving within a month of getting the job and starting work.
That's why smart employers will immediately move from the recruitment phase to the retention phase, where the path starts first and foremost with preparation and creativity right from the beginning of the recruitment process.
An efficient, structured, thoughtful hiring process will make the talent excited about their new workplace from day one and even look forward to the next.
Here are some tips on how to prepare and manage a proper recruitment process that will help retain new talent:
It's no secret -- organizational collaboration and readiness.
Share with the people who will be working with him about his recruitment, explain to them why he's vital and important to the company and the role, and how you see his contribution.
A new employee who comes to a place where he is expected and appreciated will feel welcome and will strive to prove the expectations that hang over Ben.
Knowledge is power -- alignment of expectations.
On the first day, they had an expectations call with the talent.
Get to know his professional background and see where he sees himself in the future, so you can introduce him to the diverse and unique tools that you and your workplace can provide him to get there.
We're all human beings.
During the recruitment days, try to get to know the talent beyond his professional qualities and take an interest in his hobbies and interests.
A new employee who's shown interest and allowed to express himself beyond the confines of his job will appreciate it and want to keep it.
Curiosity is driving.
Right at the recruitment stage, you can create attractiveness that makes talent want to fit in quickly.
Do it not by talking about bonuses and perks, but by exposing him to an exciting field or interesting technology, because these kinds of stimulations to creativity lead to increased curiosity and interest in the workplace.
Also, encourage the talent to voice their thoughts and opinions to the various projects in the company and make it clear to them that they are important to the organization.
The writer is the CEO of Manpower Israel.
Pocket electricity: Cost of non-closure of coal plants in June - one billion dollars
Knesset Research and Information Center report: Non-closure of coal plants by the June 2022 deadline estimated at one billion shekels
• Electricity company: "Fuel policy is primarily dictated by the Department of Energy"
I'm not going anywhere.
The economic cost of not closing coal plants by the June 2022 deadline is estimated at NIS 1 billion for 2022, according to a report by the Knesset Research and Information Center.
According to the report, this cost is reflected in the electricity price to the consumer, which is expected to rise in the coming months due to the rise in the price of coal.
In addition, an additional excess of about 900,000 tons of coal is expected to be used in 2023, resulting in additional costs to the electricity industry from the non-closure of coal plants, assuming that the price of natural gas remains significantly lower than the price of coal.
The report said that a cut of about a billion shekels in electricity tariffs by 2022 would mean a 4 percent reduction in the rate of electricity consumption for households.
That is, the economic cost of not closing stations is about a billion shekels, and the amount that could have been cut for the domestic consumer is about 4 percent.
It should be noted that as part of the reform of the electricity economy, it was decided to establish a subsidiary of the electricity company, which would set up natural gas-fired units, designed to replace the 4-1 carbon units at the Rabin Lighthouse.
Following this decision, a government decision was taken in July 2018, stating that the 4-1 coal-fired units at the Ohr Rabin power plant should cease operations.
The decision set timetables so that the construction of the first natural gas unit will begin in January 2020 and its operation will begin in June 2022, accordingly, the 4-1 carbon production units will also cease to operate at that time.
In response, the electricity company said: "Fuel policy is written first and foremost by the Department of Energy.
In accordance with the decisions of the ministry, a policy of reducing the use of coal to the minimum possible has been implemented in Israel for several years, even when the price of coal is lower than the price of gas".
