State inspector's report: the actual budget for most years of operation of the pharmaceutical basket committee is less than the recommended budget
According to the report by Methanieu Angelmann, for over 20 years of basket activity, the Ministry of Health did not oversee the committee's activities.
The report also states that meeting minutes are published significantly late, if at all.
The critic also recommends increasing the transparency of the activities of the subcommittee ¢ and updating the procedures for the work of the basket.
Another flaw is that since the committee started, the Ministry of Health has not asked the hospitals to report on the volume of use and utilization of the drugs in Basel X, which would allow them to analyze and control the budget given to them.
The Drug Basket Committee is one of the most influential public committees in our daily lives and our health.
Every year, the committee decides on new drugs to be given to the public free of charge through health insurance  but a new state inspector's report released today warns that it has been operating for more than 20 years without monitoring reports and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council overseeing and examining its activities.
Israel Today columnist Ren Reznik adds that the State Auditor's investigation was conducted in the wake of the ongoing exposures in Israel Today of drug cart manufacturers.
According to the report by Mettenjo Engelman, it recommends "to make corrections and improvements in the expansion of the basket, which will lead to a better utilization of the healthcare basket budget to which the public is entitled".
Throughout the years of existence of the mechanism of addition to the drug basket, in the years 2021-1998 medicines amounting to eight billion shekels were added to the state budget, with the addition moving annually in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million shekels.
In 2019, 2020 and 2021, requests were made to add about 800 new medicines and technologies to the healthcare basket, at a total annual cost of more than NIS 2 billion.
In fact, the budget allocated to the expansion of the basket was less than the volume of requests.
For most of the committee's years of operation (90% of the time), the amount of the budget surplus was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired surplus rate.
The complainant notes that the amount of the annual premium should be reviewed and adjusted in order to allow for certainty and long-term planning.
Angelman also noted that "the transparency model in basketball work is lacking".
Thus, for example, the rules of procedure of the Basketball Committee stipulate that minutes of meetings, which are closed to the public, are to be published within 60 days, but in practice the minutes are published 160-109 days late, with sometimes the final minutes of meetings not being published at all.
"The delay in publishing protocols impairs the transparency of decisions; therefore, it may affect the ability of proposers  hospital organizations and pharmaceutical companies  to reapply as soon as possible and appropriately, after having learned from their rejection of their proposals, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and corrected their proposals, and made a reassessment as to their readiness to be accepted in the next round", the reviewer noted in the report.
"The Ministry of Health should publish the protocols according to the schedules established in the protocol".
Of the thousands of submissions, only one financial comment was submitted.
Another criticism of Engelman concerns the preliminary procedure of evaluating the technologies submitted to the drug basket.
The reviewer found that half (46%) of the technologies submitted did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for the rejection.
Another deficiency concerns the operation of the subcommittee of the drug basket, which is closed to the media and the public, and where patient numbers and drug costs are discussed.
The reviewer recommends that a public representative be included or that the discussions be made public without confidential commercial details.
The procedure of the Health Services Basket Committee states that "an economic assessment" must be submitted for a request to add a drug to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one economic assessment has been submitted out of thousands of submissions and the committee makes its decisions without an economic assessment.
For example, for the 2021-2019 Basket Committee hearings, requests were made to add anti-obesity drugs to the basket.
The report found that the requests did not include financial estimates, including estimates of the amount that could be saved by reducing the risk of obesity-related diseases or by avoiding gastric bypass surgery.
It also suggests that the decisions of the drug basket committee are not in line with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
For example, the Ministry of Health in 2019 defined prevention medicine and preparation for the treatment of cancer growth in chronic diseases as targets, but the decisions on the expansion of the basket did not emphasize the need to achieve these goals.
The complainant also warns that since 2011 the medicine basket has also included non-hospital insurance services, including rehabilitation and portable devices and various vaccines, provided by the Ministry of Health ("third supplement").
That's when the legal framework for this step is only set in the past tense.
In the last six years, 74 million shekels from the supplement to the medicine basket have been used for these services.
Angelman recommends that the Ministry of Health update the basket work procedures and also determine whether a separate financial supplement is needed for these services.
About one-third of the new drugs that come into the drug basket are defined as "no-cost drugs", which don't cost the health insurance companies extra because they replace existing treatments.
The reviewer proposes to explore the possibility of these drugs being marketed in a different and shorter route, so that the medicine basket can be updated several times a year instead of just once a year.
There's no oversight of the use of particularly expensive drugs.
