Medical negligence at different stages of labor
In order to win damages, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that the damage was caused by negligence.
Birth is one of the most joyful and exciting events in a family's life.
But unfortunately, sometimes births end in serious birth or delivery damage caused by medical negligence.
In cases where childbirth ended in a physical injury, to the child or to the mother, there is room to examine the sequence of events that led to the injury and even to consider seeking legal counsel.
A medical malpractice attorney will examine whether there were any defects in the medical staff's conduct at the various stages of the birth that caused the harm and, where appropriate, consult a medical expert in the relevant field.
It should be emphasized that not every medical error amounts to negligence (in the legal sense of the term) and that various complications during childbirth do not necessarily teach that the treatment was negligent.
When, then, is it negligence?
When the doctor's error was due to a lack of skill or a deviation from a reasonable level of caution, and the lack of skill and deviation from the accepted level of caution caused harm to the patient that would not have been caused otherwise.
In this article, we will examine the different stages of labor, explain what complications may occur at each stage and when they amount to medical negligence.
The axis phase
The axis phase lasts on average between 8 and 14 hours.
At this stage, the cervix gradually opens (to allow passage of the fetus at birth) and should reach a diameter of about four inches [10 cm] at the end of the process.
Most cases of medical negligence in the pivotal stage involve the failure to recognize fetal distress before birth, which causes damage to the unborn child sometimes even manifesting as cerebral palsy.
Cerebral palsy:
Cerebral palsy may be caused by a failure to detect or delay the detection of a subconjunctivitis, which is manifested by a failure to supply oxygen to the fetal brain tissue.
As a rule, monitoring of the condition of the newborn and the correct placement of the fetal heart monitor should lead to early detection of fetal distress development, allowing the medical team to act quickly and rescue the newborn before it is irreversibly damaged.
Cases in which the medical team ignores signs of oxygen deprivation in the fetus or misinterpret the data in front of the fetus and on the fetal monitor or responds late to stress on the monitor may constitute negligence.
Cerebral palsy can also be caused by a fall of the umbilical cord as well as a rupture of the uterus that is not detected in time.
Even in these extreme cases, it's worthwhile to find out if the medical team acted properly.
For example, attorney Anna Reif Ligenza, of the financial firm Serrore & Co., which specializes in representing medical malpractice victims, reports that her office handled a lawsuit of a child who was injured during birth after the midwife popped the sac of spleen when the fetal head was too high, thereby causing the umbilical cord to fall (when the umbilical cord precedes the fetal head) and impaired oxygen supply to the fetal brain (as a result of the fetal head pressing on the umbilical cord) and giving birth to a severely neurologically impaired child.
In another case, a lawyer said that her office filed a lawsuit due to gross medical negligence on the part of a maternity ward staff at a large hospital who during the delivery did not recognize any obvious signs that should have led to a real suspicion that the newborn had a tear of the uterus in the area of the surgical scar of her previous pregnancy.
The fetus that escaped through the rupture into the abdominal cavity suffered severe fetal distress until it was rescued late on the verge of death.
Due to severe fetal distress during birth, the child suffered a complex neurological disability.
It should be emphasized that, in order to obtain damages, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal relationship between the negligence of the medical team that led to the breastfeeding diagnosis and the damage caused to the unborn child, that is, that the damage was caused by negligence and not by any other cause or factor.
The causal link will be established by examining medical indicators that, according to the medical literature, are the only indicators of a causal relationship between suffocation and brain injury.
Among other things, they look at the foetus' blood levels of acids, its abortion scores, the presence of neurological and systemic damage, and more.
The death of the fetus
The active stage of labor
The active stage of labor begins when the cervical opening reaches a diameter of 10 centimeters and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical stage.
In addition, the baby's birth was postponed and a caesarean section was avoided.
In some cases, a dysfunctional birth develops, Carrie, a lack of progression of the active birthing process.
In such cases, a caesarean section is usually performed to prevent various harmful effects on the fetus from delayed labor.
"There are instances when failure to perform a cesarean on time can cause irreversible damage to the fetus", explained lawyer Rafe-Ligenza.
"For example, we were handling a medical malpractice lawsuit of a stillborn child who died due to a significant delay in a C-section.
Unlike any known medical practice, medical staff were not trained to recognize fetal distress and perform a cesarean despite the extremely slow progress of the birth.
The delay in performing the surgery caused great structural damage to Luda which ultimately led to her death shortly after her birth".
Carelessness in the Birth of a Vacuum
In situations where there is a significant danger to the mother or fetus requiring a particularly rapid termination of labor, a vacuum birth is sometimes performed.
In this process, a vacuum "dope" is placed on the fetus's head and the fetus is forcibly pulled out.
Naturally, this action involves risks and can cause harm to both the fetus and the mother and therefore requires great care, accuracy, and skill.
In these cases, medical negligence may be manifested by the physician not following mandatory guidelines and performing the operation despite the existence of a contraindication, such as when the fetal head is too high in the pelvis, or performing it for too long or when despite the failure of several attempts the physician continues and repeats the operation more than the number of attempts allowed.
In these cases, if the careless vacuum action caused damage, among other things, it may cause cranial damage and bleeding that could lead to the development of brain damage, there is room for a damages claim.
Paralysis in the name of ERB
Paralysis named after Arb, this is a congenital nerve damage in the brachial plexus (a nerve junction that connects the spine to the upper part of the shoulder) and when it occurs during childbirth it is worth checking whether the damage occurred due to negligence of the birthing staff.
The injury manifests in weakness of the arm muscles and can lead to complete paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by difficulty in discharging the newborn due to the occurrence of 'paraplegia' - a congenital emergency that occurs when the fetus' shoulders are trapped inside the birth canal after its head has been removed.
When should you suspect that the paralysis was caused by medical negligence?
In cases where the weight assessment of the fetus indicates that it is a chromosomal fetus, meaning that it is expected to be born weighing more than 15 pounds [4.5 kg] and according to the guidelines it is preferable to deliver the mother by cesarean section.
When the baby weighs more than 10 pounds, a cesarean should be considered in light of risk factors, including gestational diabetes and second stage labor delays.
In the event that the medical team ignores the estimate of abnormal fetal weight or other risk factors and chooses to proceed with a vaginal birth and the risk of shoulder fracture and paralysis from ERB is realized, there is a reasonable possibility that this is medical negligence.
Indeed, in EC 2694/90, the Supreme Court ruled that "the risk of shoulder formation during birth can be predicted in advance with some degree of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder formation, where there is a risk of it occurring, is by cesarean section".
The exit phase of the placenta
The separation of the placenta from the uterus and its exit occurs due to the contraction of the uterus after the exit of the baby and is accompanied by bleeding.
The process usually lasts for up to half an hour after the baby comes out and often occurs spontaneously, without the involvement of the medical staff.
After the egg is removed, the medical team will check to see if it came out whole or if there are any parts of the egg left in the uterus.
At this stage, complications may occur that could cause serious birth defects.
One of the most common complications of uterine fibrosis is called Ashman syndrome. Uterine fibrosis is the result of inflammation caused by uterine fibrosis, a condition that affects the uterine lining to the point that the cervix cannot move.
Therefore, in cases where the medical team failed to identify any residual bone or failed to take all appropriate measures to prevent uterine fibroid injury despite suspected residual bone in the uterus, it may be a case of medical negligence and the case merits further examination by an experienced attorney.
Death at birth
A stillbirth during childbirth is a fairly rare occurrence.
In these cases, the event that was supposed to bring happiness and joy to the whole family turns, unfortunately, into the most tragic event for her.
In some cases, the medical team does not detect bleeding in the newborn in time or responds late to such bleeding.
"For example . . . ", explained attorney Reif-Lingenza, "our firm filed a claim involving a stillbirth in which the medical team ignored and failed to respond to the life-threatening signs of the birth for hours and was late in diagnosing massive and uncontrollable bleeding that was a known complication of her underlying illness".
"In another case", explained attorney Reif-Lingenza, "our firm represented the relatives of a woman who died after giving birth to twins due to hemorrhaging caused by an improperly sewn caesarean section.
In the same case, the midwife complained of severe pain and weakness after the operation, but the medical staff did not properly address her complaints and clinical condition, responding only late after her body systems began to collapse, which led to her death".
Loss of uterus
In serious cases, medical negligence at birth can lead to a hysterectomy, says lawyer Rafe Lingza: "Our firm sued a hospital on the grounds of medical negligence after childbirth.
In the same case, the woman, a 31-year-old, lost her womb due to a failure to properly treat massive bleeding observed by the medical staff after the birth and yet no action was taken in time that could have prevented the damage".
What are the compensation claims for medical negligence in childbirth?
Childbirth compensation for injury due to medical negligence at birth includes many damage components, with the most significant amounts being for pain and suffering, nursing and paid care, lost wages and pensions for the victim and even for his parents and other damage components.
The compensation awarded to an injured minor for lost wages and pensions is calculated in most cases on the basis of the average wage in the household.
Also, the compensation includes medical expenses, medical and rehabilitation equipment costs, housing adaptation costs for the baby, mobility and more.
"The amount of the compensation is determined in each case by the person and his circumstances", explains attorney Rafe-Ligenza, adding that "today most medical malpractice claims end in a settlement that weighs the chance and risk each party has in the proceedings". However, the lawyer added that "there are cases where the proceedings end only in a verdict, in which if the lawsuit is not dismissed, the plaintiffs will receive full compensation for all their damages and, for example, in a lawsuit brought by our firm, the District Court ruled that a minor who had suffered a cerebral hemorrhage due to an Irish vaginal hernia received compensation in excess of ten million shekels".
In summary
Medical negligence at birth is undoubtedly every family's nightmare.
In these cases, a proper legal examination of the sequence of events that led to the tragic outcome, by a lawyer trained in handling medical malpractice claims, can help you win the compensation you deserve.
