Research has suggested a link between the development of the disease and close marriages
The highest prevalence was in the Bedouin sector.
Expert: "It's possible that in any sector with a lot of cousin marriages, there's a high incidence of the disease".
Cartoconus is an inherited eye disease that causes some visual impairment.
It's very important to diagnose it early and find the right solutions to prevent it from getting worse.
In recent years, several studies have been conducted that help us understand how the disease develops, and innovative treatments have been developed.
The new findings provide scientific evidence to suspect that corticosteroid eye disease is a genetic disease.
A recent study, which looked at the transformation of the cornea from a forked to a scratched shape, found that the cause of corneal disease and weakness and distortion of its shape is related to an enzyme imbalance, whereby free radicals can damage the proteins in the cornea - and its structure will change.
The source of that enzyme deficiency is genetic, which supports the hypothesis that cartocinosis is an inherited disease.
According to Professor Ariella Gordon-Shag, head of the Department of Optometry at Hadassah Academy College, "In a study published in the field among Arab students in Haifa, a 3.2% incidence of cartoconus was found.
The highest prevalence was among students from the Bedouin sector -- 20 percent had cartoconus, but there was a relatively small sample".
The researcher added that this finding is not surprising: "Cartoconus is very common in the Bedouin sector.
In our studies, we found that close marriages are a risk factor for C.T.D.
So in any sector with a lot of cousin marriages, we might find a high prevalence".
In this context, it should be noted that this is an important finding in light of the unambiguous conclusion: in cases where there is a family history of CKD, all family members should have an appropriate eye exam as soon as possible.
According to Erza Proctor, a B.Sc. clinical optometrist, "there is ten times more clinic visits from remote peripheral areas, especially the southern area, than the center".
Procter adds: "Over the last decade I have noticed that most patients are coming from the periphery, especially from the Beersheba area.
This is mainly due to the high prevalence of marriages within the family (especially in the Bedouin sector) and various allergies, and the lack of awareness of proper treatment of the problem".
So how is the disease diagnosed?
Procter explains that cartoconus usually develops in adolescence or late teens (ages 16-15 or 20).
The disease involves a decrease in vision, along with an increase in cylinder capacity.
Cartoconus patients have distorted and/or blurred vision of shapes and bones.
These symptoms worsen with the development of the disease, which usually progresses slowly and gradually over years.
However, the disease may also progress rapidly and reach a peak in just a few months.
Many of the patients even show increased sensitivity to light.
