Study finds that Zoom meetings hurt creativity
Some 2,100 engineers and academics from around the world were asked to develop solutions to the problem. Some in video meetings, some in face-to-face meetings.
The result: Virtual meetings undermine creativity and thinking outside the box.
Lead researcher at Columbia University: "Visual focus on a screen interferes with the process of creating ideas"
There's no harm in productivity or critical thinking.
A large scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature examined the impact of video conferences on creativity of participants, compared to face-to-face meetings.
Unfortunately, we find that creativity does suffer in virtual meetings through screens.
The question of the study -- led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University -- was whether computer-based remote meetings preserve the creativity that occurs in office brainstorming meetings, or whether the level of creativity and free thinking decreases as a result of distance.
The study itself began as early as 2016 but received a major boost in the two years of the coronavirus, when many workers moved to work from home.
"People in a face-to-face meeting move around the room, use objects, and help them think creatively", says Brooks.
"In a computer session, however, focusing on maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative brain activity.
Visual focus on the screen reduces cognition.
People are more focused on video when interacting, which hurts the broader idea-making process".
The space is shrinking.
To test the results of the experiment and see if they would repeat themselves, they were tested twice -- once at Columbia University and once in real life -- on engineers who knew each other from early acquaintances.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty and students into two parts: one asked the subjects to meet in person and develop solutions to a problem, and the other asked them to do so via a computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to divide up in a similar way and solve a problem presented to them in a new way.
In both cases, there was a decrease in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking among those who met virtually via video.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher on ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
He believes that in mindfulness activities, people often look around to help generate ideas, whereas in video conferencing, thinking concentrates on the screen and does not expand in a way that allows for creativity.
"When people are in the same room, they look around and see the space, where there are objects and situations that can evoke new associations.
But the research shows that computer interactions change our attention so that we're more inward-focused and screen-focused, and that this way reduces innovation and idea-making through looking at the environment and thinking outside".
There's no harm in critical thinking.
However, before managers rush employees back to the offices, the researchers note that "working through a computer did not harm productivity itself or people's critical thinking about innovative proposals, when they had to pick the best idea from a set of ideas.
I mean, the impact is only on creativity and not other forms of computer work".
Professor Ellen Langer, a professor of psychology at Harvard University, also disputes the findings.
She says, "There is a difference between mere creativity, like new uses for PRIZBY, and work solutions.
It's also possible that when employees are more relaxed after getting to know each other, or when they work from home, creativity actually improves".
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson have also proposed a future study in which meetings like this would stop thinking states and wander around a room to see how this activity would affect the end result.
Dr. Olson also suggested that the study would only result in brainstorming sessions for employees to return to work and generally suggested that one study should not be frightening, but that more research should be done in the field.
"I wouldn't want workers to be forcibly laid off and not be happy. That's a bigger injury", he says.
