By 2050, the world will have lost 80% of the water available for agriculture.
A new global study predicts a significant decline in the next 25 years
The Solution: Proper Water Management
A disturbing new study recently published in the journal Earth's Future predicts that by 2050, the amount of water available for agriculture will shrink by 80 percent if the rate of water use and population growth in the world continues at current usage trends.
In the study, which involved scientists from all the world's science agencies, scientists summarized the total amount of rainwater, rivers and freshwater resources in the world and compared it to humanity's need for agriculture.
The grim findings of the study show that the rate of water consumption is now doubling over and over again in the last 10 years, while global warming is causing less rainfall in agricultural areas around the world.
According to the study's data, 84 percent of the world's agricultural land will experience severe rainwater shortages.
One of the key findings from the study is that farmers around the world should adapt their farming to climate change and seasonal changes, and switch to farming methods that focus on water infiltration into the soil to prevent the process of water depletion that leads to widespread waste of rainwater.
The researchers also recommend that farmers working near saltwater sources use rainwater harvesting technologies to prevent it from flowing into the sea.
