We looked: What do the side effects of the coronavirus vaccine mean?
Many people who inject feel weak, feverish, and tired after receiving an injection, while others do not feel a thing.
Could this indicate a stronger immune system in those who do experience these symptoms, or is this just a disproven rumor?
While more and more people are vaccinated, the lack of information about side effects continues to confuse and create rumors, most of which are false.
Is the immune system of those who developed side effects stronger than those whose bodies responded less severely to the vaccine, which may prove that their system is unable to fight off a foreign body entering the body?
"There are several levels of responses to the vaccine", says Dr. David Devere, chief of primary care at the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and a member of the CDC's Advisory Committee on Epidemiology, and reassuringly: "Headaches, fatigue, sore spots, these are the immediate responses of the immune system.
That's how the body responds to foreign bodies entering the system".
Is there a link between the levels of antibodies that develop and the side effects?
"There's no correlation between sensitivity and the development of antibodies to the virus.
About 60 to 50 percent experience side effects, but about 90 percent develop immunity to the virus.
We didn't find that people who developed stronger responses were more protected".
"There is no correlation in the medical literature between immediate response and vaccine levels.
In some of the trials where people also received placebo vaccines, about a quarter of them developed headaches.
It's also a psychological component -- how a person reacts to the vaccine, if they expect side effects.
Many of the events that occurred could also have occurred normally, but because the public is immune, they attribute the response to the vaccine itself, and this is a misconception that we see about vaccines in general -- the attribution of events that occur near and attributable to the vaccine".
According to Dr. Deaver, the causes of the reported well-being symptoms, such as weakness and headaches, are not yet known.
On the subject of myocarditis, opinions are divided.
"There are all sorts of theories about it, but it's worth noting that the virus itself causes higher rates of mycorrhiza than the vaccine.
One theory is that it's a strong immune response".
Is there even a way to gauge the strength of an immune system?
"When students were exposed to the flu virus, it was shown that those who did not sleep or were under higher stress were more susceptible to infection.
Besides, there are laboratory parameters that test the immune system or its components.
When there's a drop in the immune system, you can see it immediately.
People get a lot of viral or infectious diseases.
It's not like someone's walking around with a weak immune system and not knowing it.
These are people who come to the clinic because of recurrent episodes of infectious disease, and what affects the system are mundane things: stress, diet, sleep.
By the way, we also don't want a too strong immune system, because it can cause autoimmune diseases".
MRNA vaccines will soon appear in more contexts, thanks to the vast amount of information that has been accumulated about them in recent times.
"It will certainly pave the way for other such vaccines.
This technology is being tested for a lot of applications beyond vaccines -- for treating oncological diseases, for example.
Their effectiveness is that the substance stays in the body for a very short time -- enters, does its job, and then breaks down.
This technology isn't new, but it's received a major boost in response to the overwhelming need for rapid vaccination.
Now, for example, we know that the three-week gap between doses is too small, and some vaccine experts say that after a third dose, we may not need another vaccine anytime soon, so it's not clear if we're going to get to a six-monthly vaccine or if a third dose will give a bigger gap".
