Your personal information, including your full name, addresses, payment amounts and full details of the trips you have booked, may be revealed.
According to the Privacy Authority, Via-Earth violated the Privacy Act and its regulations.
Following a report that a company operating Israel's Route 6 road, Via Aretz, had reported a security incident at the company, the Privacy Authority began enforcement proceedings.
As part of the event, security vulnerabilities were discovered on its payment website, which allowed for the exposure of a large amount of information from the member's customers' accounts, which were exposed to the public.
Among other things, customer bills were exposed over a relatively short period of time and these bills included personal information, including first and last name, payment amounts, vehicle location, travel dates and times.
Furthermore, because a transit company did not log access to its systems as required by law, it is not possible to know exactly how long unauthorized parties could access the company's systems.
In the breach letter, which the Privacy Authority sent to the company, the Authority emphasized that most companies and large organizations in the economy are required to adopt a dynamic information security policy, and that as threats and risks evolve, the organization has an obligation to carefully consider the updated risks and act according to the updated security measures accepted in the circumstances, depending on the nature and quality of the database.
As a result, companies and organizations have an obligation to update their systems and conduct risk reviews and penetration tests to assess and prepare for changing risks.
Companies and organizations are also required to use an automated recording mechanism and must provide training to employees, in accordance with the provisions of the Privacy (information security) regulations.
Based on the findings of the review, the Authority determined that the company had violated the provisions of the Privacy Protection Act and its regulations and required the company to take a number of corrective actions.
"The matter has been handled in accordance with the strictest requirements".
